created the Red Coast Self-Interpreting Code System.

259
00:21:20.610 --> 00:21:25.460
At that time, the Cold War was at its height.

260
00:21:26.130 --> 00:21:31.540
The insanity of the human race had reached its historical zenith.

261
00:21:31.540 --> 00:21:37.130
Nuclear submarines and nuclear weapons lurking in the corners

262
00:21:37.130 --> 00:21:40.540
could be launched at a moment's notice.

263
00:21:40.540 --> 00:21:45.580
Once they were let go, hundreds of cities would be leveled,

264
00:21:45.580 --> 00:21:47.560
killing hundreds of millions of people.

265
00:21:48.500 --> 00:21:50.980
With such technical leaps in sight,

266
00:21:50.980 --> 00:21:56.480
an intense sense of crisis was shared all over the world.

267
00:21:58.440 --> 00:22:01.720
Professor Ye, you're an astrophysicist.

268
00:22:01.720 --> 00:22:06.070
Do you really think astronomy will be taking a technological leap?

269
00:22:06.070 --> 00:22:10.090
As destructive as nukes are,

270
00:22:10.090 --> 00:22:14.400
the universe is harboring even more terrible forces

271
00:22:14.400 --> 00:22:18.300
such as black holes and anti-matter.

272
00:22:18.300 --> 00:22:21.220
Compared with them,

273
00:22:21.220 --> 00:22:26.250
a nuclear bomb is nothing but a tiny candle.

274
00:22:28.540 --> 00:22:34.540
There used to be a waveform monitor.

275
00:22:34.540 --> 00:22:40.080
It was to display the waves that Red Coast picked up from space.

276
00:22:41.060 --> 00:22:47.020
My daily work was to monitor and record that curve,

277
00:22:48.440 --> 00:22:53.710
waiting to hear from the extraterrestrials.

278
00:23:02.680 --> 00:23:05.080
Over there,

279
00:23:05.080 --> 00:23:09.860
we had a radio receiver,

280
00:23:09.860 --> 00:23:12.520
quite sophisticated.

281
00:23:12.520 --> 00:23:16.020
A ruby-based traveling-wave maser amplified

282
00:23:16.020 --> 00:23:20.530
the signals received by the gigantic antenna.

283
00:23:21.750 --> 00:23:24.780
But there was interference.

284
00:23:24.780 --> 00:23:27.920
Wouldn't it affect the accuracy?

285
00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:33.430
Wang, you're underestimating Red Coast.

286
00:23:34.610 --> 00:23:40.210
As immature as the technology was,

287
00:23:40.210 --> 00:23:44.410
it could do more than you think.

288
00:23:44.410 --> 00:23:47.740
The core of the reception system

289
00:23:47.740 --> 00:23:51.740
was immersed in liquid helium at -269 degrees Celsius.

290
00:23:51.740 --> 00:23:58.130
A helicopter came to resupply liquid helium regularly.

291
00:23:58.130 --> 00:24:02.980
The reception system was thus

292
00:24:02.980 --> 00:24:06.990
capable of picking up faint signals.

293
00:24:06.990 --> 00:24:14.200
Back then, our monitoring range was within a radius of 1,000 light years,

294
00:24:14.200 --> 00:24:17.510
containing some 20 million stars.

295
00:24:17.510 --> 00:24:22.930
Other than searching for and monitoring possible extraterrestrial intelligence,

296
00:24:22.930 --> 00:24:24.850
we also tried to

297
00:24:24.850 --> 00:24:28.310
send messages to the universe 
 <i>[20 Million Stars]</i>

298
00:24:28.310 --> 00:24:33.170
to establish contact and communication.

299
00:24:33.980 --> 00:24:39.730
So did you really make such attempts?

300
00:24:44.450 --> 00:24:45.390
We did.

301
